	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Review of the implications of the EU’s evolving banana regime</h1>

			
			<h4>
												05 July 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A European Parliament research report on the implications of recent changes in the EU banana regime has been published. The report starts by reviewing the three phases of the banana dispute since 1993. These were:</p>
<ul>

<li>Phase 1: 1993–99. Characterised by litigation over the legal compatibility of the EC arrangement.</li>

<li>Phase 2: 1999–2005. Characterised by negotiations with main exporters on tariff issues.</li>

<li>Phase 3: 2005–2011. Characterised by pressure to further reduce tariffs linked to the Doha Round negotiations.</li>

</ul>
<p>The policy part of the study analyses trade data and uses macro-economic modelling to assess the impact of changes. This analysis argues that ‘the adverse effect of the Geneva agreement for ACP countries is somewhat mitigated by the increase in EU imports and, for non-traditional ACP producers, by the positive effect of the EPAs.’ It maintains that ‘the net effects of both EPAs and the Geneva agreement are expected to be positive for ACP countries, slightly negative for Latin American countries and indifferent for EU producers’.</p><p>Recent EU bilateral agreements with Latin American exporters are expected to ‘further erode the preferential access of ACP producers and of other Latin American exporters to the EU’, with these countries expected to experience ‘a decline in relative competitiveness’, exporting less to the EU and receiving a lower price for their exports.</p><p>However overall the changes in the EU banana regime are ‘likely to impose considerable adjustment costs; mainly on the Caribbean exporters’, with ‘limited costs for some African exporters (Cameroon and Côte d’Ivoire), with the latter partly replacing Caribbean exports. The greatest need for adjustment assistance is therefore in the Caribbean. This, it is argued, should be reflected in the financial allocations of the EU’s banana accompanying measures (BAM) programme. It is also argued that BAM programme interventions should ‘take notice of the lessons from previous similar schemes’ so as not to repeat past mistakes under other similar support programmes.</p><p>Meanwhile, analysis of Eurostat trade data published by Le Hub Rural shows banana exports from Ghana, the Dominican Republic and Suriname to the EU increasing 43%, 33% and 22% respectively in 2010, in the face of weather-affected production in Ecuador, Colombia and the Windward Islands (see table). Press reports also indicate the emergence of new patterns of intra-regional trade in bananas in the Caribbean.</p><p><b>Main trends in ACP banana exports to the EU (tonnes)</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" width="593">
